231","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1202":"1202","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1319":"1319","1209":"1209","about 1230":"circa 1230","Methil, Fife, Scotland":"Methil, Fife, Schotland","Leuchars, Fife, Scotland":"Leuchars, Fife, Schotland","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Schotland","Wemyss, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Schotland"},"en":{"1231–1319":"1231–1319","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1209–1304":"1209–1304","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1202":"1202","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1319":"1319","1209":"1209","about 1230":"about 1230","Methil, Fife, Scotland":"Methil, Fife, Scotland","Leuchars, Fife, Scotland":"Leuchars, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wemyss","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Wemyss in Fife, traditionally pronounced ‘weems’. The placename is from Gaelic <i>uaimh</i> ‘cave’ + the placename forming suffix <i>–es</i>. The surname reached Ireland in the 14th century, see   Wims  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wims","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Wemyss  , representing the usual pronunciation of that Scottish name."]},{"name":"Weems","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Wemyss  , reflecting the usual pronunciation of that name.","History: David Weems (Wemyss) emigrated from Scotland to Herring Bay, Anne Arundel County, MD, some time before 1722. Mason Locke Weems, born near Herring Bay in 1759, was a clergyman who wrote a biography of George Washington, in which the first account of the cherry-tree story appeared."]},{"name":"Wymbs","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Wemyss  . Compare   Wims  ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Wemyss","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Wemyss in Fife, traditionally pronounced ‘weems’. The placename is from Gaelic <i>uaimh</i> ‘cave’ + the placename forming suffix <i>–es</i>. The surname reached Ireland in the 14th century, see   Wims  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wims","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Wemyss  , representing the usual pronunciation of that Scottish name."]},{"name":"Weems","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Wemyss  , reflecting the usual pronunciation of that name.","History: David Weems (Wemyss) emigrated from Scotland to Herring Bay, Anne Arundel County, MD, some time before 1722. Mason Locke Weems, born near Herring Bay in 1759, was a clergyman who wrote a biography of George Washington, in which the first account of the cherry-tree story appeared."]},{"name":"Wymbs","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Wemyss  . Compare   Wims  ."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Michael Wemyss - Lord of Wemyss was born in 1231, in Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, his father, Sir John Wemyss - Lord of Methil and Wemyss, was 29 and his mother, Amabilla De Wemyss, was 22. He married Agatha Lochore in 1262. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1319, in his hometown, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1231–1319":"1231–1319","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1209–1304":"1209–1304","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1202":"1202","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1319":"1319","1209":"1209","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Methil, Fife, Scotland":"Methil, Fife, Scotland","Leuchars, Fife, Scotland":"Leuchars, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland"},"fi":{"1231–1319":"1231–1319","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1209–1304":"1209–1304","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1202":"1202","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1319":"1319","1209":"1209","about 1230":"noin 1230","Methil, Fife, Scotland":"Methil, Fife, Scotland","Leuchars, Fife, Scotland":"Leuchars, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland","Wemyss, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland"},"fr":{"1231–1319":"1231–1319","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1240–1325":"1240–1325","1263–1325":"1263–1325","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1202–1263":"1202–1263","1209–1304":"1209–1304","1231":"1231","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1202":"1202","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1319":"1319","1209":"1209"